WEBVTT

00:03.786 --> 00:06.310
[sirens wailing]

00:06.354 --> 00:09.313
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.357 --> 00:11.402
- [coughing]

00:11.446 --> 00:14.101
[whimpering]
- Hang on, Hannah, okay?

00:14.144 --> 00:21.064
<i>♪ </i>

00:21.108 --> 00:23.719
[ambulance doors opening]

00:26.591 --> 00:28.724
[hydraulics droning]

00:28.767 --> 00:30.813
- [whimpers]

00:30.856 --> 00:33.816
- I love you.
- Will...

00:33.859 --> 00:40.301
<i>♪ </i>

00:40.344 --> 00:42.303
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

00:51.268 --> 00:52.661
[elevator dings]

00:56.143 --> 00:57.753
[suitcase rumbles]

01:00.886 --> 01:04.194
<i>[computer scans, beeps]</i>

01:09.634 --> 01:11.332
<i>[beeping]</i>

01:14.596 --> 01:16.424
- Dr. Halstead.

01:16.467 --> 01:17.686
- Doris.

01:17.729 --> 01:19.514
- Any symptoms?
Headache, dry cough?

01:19.557 --> 01:20.689
- Nope.

01:20.732 --> 01:21.733
- 98.5.
Good.

01:21.777 --> 01:22.821
Ope.
Let's get you tested.

01:22.865 --> 01:24.127
- I was just tested
this morning.

01:24.171 --> 01:25.520
- You went home.

01:25.563 --> 01:28.131
Nobody goes back in the E.D.
without getting tested.

01:28.175 --> 01:30.220
Come on.
Come up.

01:30.264 --> 01:31.308
Open up.

01:31.352 --> 01:33.223
<i>♪ </i>

01:33.267 --> 01:34.268
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

01:34.311 --> 01:35.573
- Jim, a word?

01:35.617 --> 01:38.272
- Let's take it inside.
I need a break.

01:50.675 --> 01:52.373
- Hey.

01:52.416 --> 01:55.202
This is April's third straight
week in the COVID ward.

01:55.245 --> 01:57.421
- We're short-staffed.
April volunteered.

01:57.465 --> 01:59.380
- Protocol is one week on,
one week off.

01:59.423 --> 02:00.816
She's putting herself at risk.

02:00.859 --> 02:02.339
- I don't know
what to tell you.

02:02.383 --> 02:04.254
April feels this
is her mission.

02:04.298 --> 02:05.516
- Jim, you're
the chief of the E.D.

02:05.560 --> 02:06.604
You've gotta protect
your staff.

02:06.648 --> 02:08.171
- She knows what she's doing.

02:08.215 --> 02:10.826
What's it to you?
I thought you guys broke up.

02:10.869 --> 02:12.741
- Has nothing to do with it.

02:12.784 --> 02:16.353
- Ethan, I need her.
Okay?

02:16.397 --> 02:18.790
Check your iPad.
You got five patients.

02:18.834 --> 02:20.183
You know the drill.

02:20.227 --> 02:21.445
Monitor them
from outside the room.

02:21.489 --> 02:23.360
Leave it to the nurses inside
to treat them.

02:23.404 --> 02:24.535
[gloves crumple]

02:24.579 --> 02:26.189
- Dr. Halstead.

02:26.233 --> 02:28.191
COVID test was negative.
You're good to go.

02:28.235 --> 02:31.194
<i>[tense music]</i>

02:31.238 --> 02:34.937
<i>♪ </i>

02:34.980 --> 02:36.460
<i>[machinery beeping]</i>

02:36.504 --> 02:38.462
<i>[alarm beeps]</i>

02:38.506 --> 02:39.985
<i>[rapid chiming]</i>

02:40.029 --> 02:42.292
[disinfectant spraying]

02:46.557 --> 02:48.516
<i>[chimes]</i>

02:57.351 --> 02:58.656
<i>[rapid chiming]</i>

02:58.700 --> 02:59.875
<i>[chimes]</i>

02:59.918 --> 03:03.487
[machine droning]

03:06.708 --> 03:09.319
[machinery beeping]

03:09.363 --> 03:16.370
<i>♪ </i>

03:17.371 --> 03:19.286
<i>-</i>Hannah's sats dropped
and we couldn't recover 'em,

03:19.329 --> 03:20.591
so we intubated.

03:20.635 --> 03:21.897
- Figured you'd have to.

03:21.940 --> 03:24.508
- Now it looks she
has a chemical pneumonitis--

03:24.552 --> 03:26.336
aspirated some vomit.

03:26.380 --> 03:29.861
So I put an OG tube down to
decompress her stomach, okay?

03:29.905 --> 03:33.517
Hey, Will.
She's gonna be okay.

03:33.561 --> 03:34.823
- Yeah.
Thanks.

03:34.866 --> 03:36.781
Crockett, I'm glad
you're taking care of her.

03:36.825 --> 03:38.000
- You got it.

03:38.043 --> 03:39.349
- Hey.

03:39.393 --> 03:41.308
I just got a text.
Hannah was brought in?

03:41.351 --> 03:43.440
- Yeah.

03:43.484 --> 03:44.702
- Well, she's in here.

03:44.746 --> 03:46.704
So it can't be COVID.

03:47.792 --> 03:48.880
- Um...

03:48.924 --> 03:51.535
I found her unconscious
in her bathroom,

03:51.579 --> 03:53.450
syringe in her arm.

03:53.494 --> 03:54.973
<i>♪ </i>

03:55.017 --> 03:58.542
She OD'd.

03:58.586 --> 04:01.545
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

04:01.589 --> 04:03.895
<i>♪ </i>

04:07.856 --> 04:09.379
- Good.
Fine.

04:09.423 --> 04:11.338
<i>- Got your energy back?</i>

04:11.381 --> 04:12.991
- Sharon, I am ready
to go back to work.

04:13.035 --> 04:14.384
Trust me.

04:14.428 --> 04:16.647
<i>- Well, good.
You've been missed.</i>

04:16.691 --> 04:18.214
- How you been doing?

04:18.258 --> 04:20.695
<i>- Well, the board still
doesn't want me coming back</i>

04:20.738 --> 04:22.349
<i>because of my diabetes.</i>

04:22.392 --> 04:25.482
<i>So all of my meetings
are virtual.</i>

04:25.526 --> 04:29.312
<i>Look--Zooming with,
like, ten people,</i>

04:29.356 --> 04:30.748
<i>all in their little box.</i>

04:30.792 --> 04:31.923
<i>It's driving me crazy.</i>

04:31.967 --> 04:33.621
<i>I can't read the room.</i>

04:33.664 --> 04:36.014
<i>I don't know
if people are, like,</i>

04:36.058 --> 04:38.495
<i>actually paying attention</i>

04:38.539 --> 04:40.889
<i>or just looking down
at their phones.</i>

04:40.932 --> 04:42.412
- Yeah, there's already
a name for that.

04:42.456 --> 04:43.935
They're calling it
"Zoom fatigue."

04:43.979 --> 04:46.329
I've already read, like,
three psych papers on it.

04:46.373 --> 04:47.852
<i>- Hey, and speaking of psych,</i>

04:47.896 --> 04:50.028
<i>I need you to carve out time
for the staff.</i>

04:50.072 --> 04:52.944
<i>There's--there's
just been no let-up</i>

04:52.988 --> 04:54.642
<i>with the workload.</i>

04:54.685 --> 04:56.774
<i>And so many fatalities.</i>

04:56.818 --> 04:58.341
<i>And then you add to that</i>

04:58.385 --> 05:00.735
<i>all the social trauma
they've been dealing with.</i>

05:00.778 --> 05:02.780
<i>I'm sending out a memo now.</i>

05:02.824 --> 05:04.565
- Great.
Good.

05:04.608 --> 05:05.783
<i>- And is Anna with you?</i>

05:05.827 --> 05:07.611
- Yeah.
Yeah.

05:07.655 --> 05:11.528
We decided that, you know, it
was safe for her to come back.

05:11.572 --> 05:13.791
<i>- Well, say hi for me, okay?</i>

05:13.835 --> 05:14.836
- Will do.

05:14.879 --> 05:17.055
Okay.
Take care of yourself.

05:17.099 --> 05:18.927
<i>- Take care.</i>

05:19.710 --> 05:20.842
<i>[computer program closes]</i>

05:20.885 --> 05:23.061
[knocking on door]

05:23.105 --> 05:24.846
[door opens]

05:26.021 --> 05:28.589
- Good morning.

05:28.632 --> 05:30.721
Uh, Sharon Goodwin says hi.

05:32.419 --> 05:36.031
So, I-I'm going to work.

05:36.074 --> 05:38.076
Uh....

05:38.120 --> 05:40.557
You're pretty much
gonna stay put.

05:40.601 --> 05:42.951
- Dad, I'm not gonna go out.
- That's good.

05:42.994 --> 05:46.389
Because, I mean, it's a--
- I know.

05:48.696 --> 05:51.873
- Okay.
I'll--I'll see you later.

05:53.048 --> 05:55.006
- Bye.

06:01.099 --> 06:03.798
[phone ringing]

06:03.841 --> 06:05.016
- Whoa! Sorry.
Sorry, Crockett.

06:05.060 --> 06:06.061
- Whoa, Manning.
Eyes on the road.

06:06.104 --> 06:07.062
- Sorry.
- Oh, hey.

06:07.105 --> 06:08.150
- Yeah?

06:08.193 --> 06:10.761
- I heard you moved
into Club Med.

06:10.805 --> 06:12.415
- The Pavilion.
Yes.

06:12.459 --> 06:14.417
Yes, I am.
- Oh.

06:14.461 --> 06:16.027
Well, watch yourself.

06:16.071 --> 06:18.029
I hear it gets
pretty rowdy in there.

06:18.073 --> 06:20.205
Lot of questionable behavior.

06:20.249 --> 06:21.903
- Mm.
Okay.

06:21.946 --> 06:23.426
- Nat?
- Yes.

06:23.470 --> 06:26.429
- Check your iPad.
You're going to Treatment Four.

06:26.473 --> 06:27.778
- Got it.

06:27.822 --> 06:29.476
See you, Crockett.

06:29.519 --> 06:31.042
- All right.

06:31.086 --> 06:33.001
- Mr. Lieu?
Hi.

06:33.044 --> 06:34.568
I'm Dr. Manning.

06:34.611 --> 06:35.873
And you must be Kellie.

06:35.917 --> 06:37.701
- Hi.
- Hi.

06:37.745 --> 06:40.748
I see Kellie's been dealing
with myelogenous leukemia?

06:40.791 --> 06:41.966
- For a couple years.

06:42.010 --> 06:43.315
She's immunocompromised,

06:43.359 --> 06:44.534
so I didn't want to bring her
into the hospital

06:44.578 --> 06:46.057
if I didn't need to.

06:46.101 --> 06:48.843
But she was in remission,
but her leukemia came back.

06:48.886 --> 06:50.975
So we had to do chemo all over.

06:51.019 --> 06:53.151
Just finished the last
round eight weeks ago.

06:53.195 --> 06:55.458
Just hope she won't have
to do it again.

06:55.502 --> 06:57.721
- Let me see.

06:57.765 --> 06:59.244
<i>[tense music]</i>

06:59.288 --> 07:01.464
You're having difficulty
breathing, aren't you?

07:01.508 --> 07:03.466
- It's okay.
I'm used to it.

07:03.510 --> 07:05.729
<i>♪ </i>

07:05.773 --> 07:09.820
- Well, we're gonna
help you feel better, okay?

07:09.864 --> 07:13.868
Let's get a CBC, a BMP, an ECG,
an echo, and a BNP, okay?

07:13.911 --> 07:15.130
- You got it.

07:15.173 --> 07:17.785
- You mind if I talk
to your dad for a moment?

07:17.828 --> 07:19.221
Okay.

07:19.264 --> 07:24.226
<i>♪ </i>

07:24.269 --> 07:27.490
So, I am hearing
an S3 gallop in her heart

07:27.534 --> 07:28.752
which means it's struggling.

07:28.796 --> 07:30.841
Also, her neck veins
are distended.

07:30.885 --> 07:33.931
And I am seeing some swelling
in her legs and ankles.

07:33.975 --> 07:36.717
- Those are symptoms
of heart failure, aren't they?

07:36.760 --> 07:39.284
Her oncologist warned us
about that.

07:39.328 --> 07:41.852
- It's most likely a result
of the chemo medication.

07:41.896 --> 07:44.115
Unfortunately,
some are cardiotoxic.

07:44.159 --> 07:46.161
They can damage
the heart muscle.

07:46.204 --> 07:48.555
The good news is
I think we can reverse it

07:48.598 --> 07:50.121
if we change her medication.

07:50.165 --> 07:51.601
So let's get
the test results back,

07:51.645 --> 07:53.821
and then I will loop in
your oncologist, okay?

07:53.864 --> 07:55.039
- Okay.
- All right.

07:55.083 --> 07:56.693
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

07:56.737 --> 07:58.521
<i>♪ </i>

07:58.565 --> 08:00.654
<i>- Clear.</i>

08:00.697 --> 08:03.613
<i>[machinery beeping]</i>

08:03.657 --> 08:05.702
- Mr. Booker?

08:05.746 --> 08:08.879
<i>I'm afraid your x-ray
looks wet.</i>

08:08.923 --> 08:11.055
- That means that you still
have fluid in your lungs.

08:11.099 --> 08:13.536
The proning hasn't helped.

08:13.580 --> 08:15.320
<i>- So what now?</i>

08:15.364 --> 08:18.149
<i>- I suggest we intubate
and put you on a ventilator.</i>

08:18.193 --> 08:19.150
<i>- A ventilator?</i>

08:19.194 --> 08:20.543
- You would be sedated.

08:20.587 --> 08:21.936
<i>- I don't feel that bad.</i>

08:21.979 --> 08:23.720
- I know, but the thing
that makes people feel bad--

08:23.764 --> 08:24.939
a rise in C02--

08:24.982 --> 08:26.288
doesn't happen with COVID.

08:26.331 --> 08:28.290
But you're still not
getting enough oxygen.

08:28.333 --> 08:30.248
If we put you on a ventilator,
it'll allow you to rest.

08:30.292 --> 08:31.554
<i>- Please.</i>

08:31.598 --> 08:32.686
<i>Can't you wait
a little longer?</i>

08:32.729 --> 08:33.991
<i>Make sure I really need it?</i>

08:34.035 --> 08:36.690
<i>- If we wait and you go
into cardiac arrest,</i>

08:36.733 --> 08:38.082
<i>we can't resuscitate you.</i>

08:38.126 --> 08:39.649
- I know it's terrible.

08:39.693 --> 08:41.651
But we can't run
a code in here.

08:41.695 --> 08:44.219
Chest compressions release
so much virus.

08:44.262 --> 08:46.308
- Please, Alvin.

08:46.351 --> 08:48.136
Let us help you.

08:48.179 --> 08:50.181
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:50.225 --> 08:52.183
<i>- Okay.
- Okay.</i>

08:52.227 --> 08:54.142
20 of etomidate, 100 of roc?

08:54.185 --> 08:55.839
<i>- And start
a propofol infusion.</i>

08:55.883 --> 08:57.319
I need to suit up.

08:57.362 --> 08:59.626
I gotta go in to intubate.

08:59.669 --> 09:02.846
- Dr. Marcel, look alive.
Incoming GSW.

09:02.890 --> 09:04.065
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

09:04.108 --> 09:06.023
<i>[alarm blaring]</i>

09:06.067 --> 09:07.895
- 20-year-old male,
COVID negative,

09:07.938 --> 09:09.200
gunshot wound
to the upper right thigh,

09:09.244 --> 09:11.855
GCS 15, BP 100/77.

09:11.899 --> 09:14.597
- It hurts.
- Gonna take care of that, bud.

09:14.641 --> 09:17.121
50 of Fentanyl.
X-rays, meet us inside.

09:17.165 --> 09:18.862
- Gunshot wound?
- [sighs]

09:18.906 --> 09:20.298
Second one today.

09:20.342 --> 09:22.736
- COVID or no COVID,
some things never change.

09:22.779 --> 09:24.825
- How are we ever
gonna heal this city?

09:24.868 --> 09:27.784
<i>♪ </i>

09:27.828 --> 09:29.743
- I know what
you're gonna say.

09:29.786 --> 09:31.309
"I told you so."

09:31.353 --> 09:33.398
- Why would I say that?

09:33.442 --> 09:35.618
- You said drug addicts can
replace drugs with romance.

09:35.662 --> 09:36.924
Ring a bell?

09:36.967 --> 09:40.057
- Well, I mean, it happens.

09:40.101 --> 09:42.146
- Well, not with us.

09:42.190 --> 09:43.887
We love each other.

09:43.931 --> 09:45.236
Okay?

09:45.280 --> 09:46.847
Yeah, uh, sure.

09:46.890 --> 09:48.065
There's stress
because of the pandemic.

09:48.109 --> 09:49.632
But everybody's feeling that.

09:49.676 --> 09:51.895
And maybe 'cause
of the quarantine,

09:51.939 --> 09:53.375
we moved in sooner
than we would've.

09:53.418 --> 09:54.898
- Totally understandable.

09:54.942 --> 09:56.857
I mean, trust me.
You are not the only ones.

09:56.900 --> 09:58.336
- But we're making it work.

09:58.380 --> 10:00.948
What happened last night
was a lapse.

10:00.991 --> 10:02.079
That's all.

10:02.123 --> 10:03.733
- Will, look.

10:03.777 --> 10:05.169
I'm not here
to confront you, buddy.

10:05.213 --> 10:07.650
I mean, these sessions
are about one thing

10:07.694 --> 10:08.782
and one thing only,

10:08.825 --> 10:11.436
and that is lowering
your stress levels

10:11.480 --> 10:14.091
in a time when practicing
emergency medicine

10:14.135 --> 10:16.137
can--can be overwhelming.

10:16.180 --> 10:19.662
You know?
And that's it.

10:19.706 --> 10:21.229
Does that sound okay?

10:26.234 --> 10:27.670
- I'm sorry.

10:27.714 --> 10:29.150
I haven't even asked
how you're doing.

10:29.193 --> 10:31.674
I understand you had
a pretty bad time with it.

10:31.718 --> 10:35.112
- Yeah, you know,
this COVID thing ain't no joke.

10:35.156 --> 10:37.027
But you know what?
I'm fine.

10:37.071 --> 10:39.334
And, look, I really
appreciate your asking

10:39.377 --> 10:42.903
but I really wanna use
this time if it's okay

10:42.946 --> 10:45.862
to talk about you, you know,
and how you're doing.

10:47.385 --> 10:50.432
- I'm managing, I guess.

10:50.475 --> 10:52.739
I mean, we finally
have enough PPE.

10:52.782 --> 10:54.958
And the safety protocols
seem to be working.

10:55.002 --> 10:56.090
- Okay.
Good.

10:56.133 --> 10:58.135
<i>♪ </i>

10:58.179 --> 11:00.790
- I just...

11:00.834 --> 11:02.226
- What?

11:02.270 --> 11:04.446
<i>♪ </i>

11:04.489 --> 11:07.405
- I thought we'd be
over it by now.

11:12.193 --> 11:14.151
- [sighs]
Three weeks straight.

11:14.195 --> 11:16.240
- [sighs]
Don't start, Ethan.

11:16.284 --> 11:18.852
- You're putting yourself
at risk.

11:18.895 --> 11:20.854
- Look around.

11:20.897 --> 11:24.727
So many of these patients...

11:24.771 --> 11:26.511
I see the people
I grew up with.

11:26.555 --> 11:28.513
They're dying
at twice the rate.

11:28.557 --> 11:30.080
- I know.
I know.

11:30.124 --> 11:33.214
- They've been discriminated
against their entire lives.

11:33.257 --> 11:35.869
Poverty, terrible healthcare.

11:35.912 --> 11:37.174
- And now they're here
with this.

11:37.218 --> 11:38.915
- Yeah.

11:38.959 --> 11:41.309
- Wait.

11:41.352 --> 11:43.267
I'm just worried about you.

11:43.311 --> 11:45.487
- The two men I'm treating,

11:45.530 --> 11:48.185
they are sick.

11:48.229 --> 11:49.970
They are frightened.

11:50.013 --> 11:52.407
And they are alone.

11:52.450 --> 11:55.279
I'm not abandoning them.

11:55.323 --> 11:59.066
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:02.417 --> 12:04.288
[hand sanitizer station
squeaks]

12:04.332 --> 12:06.029
- Ms. Palmer, hi.
I'm Dr. Halstead.

12:06.073 --> 12:07.727
- Hiya.
Call me Anita.

12:07.770 --> 12:09.250
- Okay.
- Mm.

12:09.293 --> 12:11.121
- This is her husband, Brad.

12:11.165 --> 12:14.037
- Hey, Brad.
Sorry you can't be here.

12:14.081 --> 12:15.909
We're limiting visitors
for safety.

12:15.952 --> 12:17.214
<i>- No, I understand.</i>

12:17.258 --> 12:18.476
- Okay.
Thank you.

12:18.520 --> 12:20.783
- Is it true redheads
like spicy food?

12:20.827 --> 12:23.003
- [chuckles]
Uh, I haven't heard that one.

12:23.046 --> 12:24.744
[laughter]

12:24.787 --> 12:26.484
So, Anita, you had a fall
today, huh?

12:26.528 --> 12:27.790
- Yeah.

12:27.834 --> 12:29.966
In the kitchen after breakfast.
- Okay.

12:30.010 --> 12:31.751
You hurt your arm?
- Mm-hmm.

12:31.794 --> 12:33.317
- Yeah.
- [winces]

12:33.361 --> 12:35.755
- Did you lose consciousness?
- No.

12:35.798 --> 12:38.235
- Oh.
What happened here?

12:38.279 --> 12:39.889
- Oh.
[laughs]

12:39.933 --> 12:41.499
That was a couple of days ago.

12:41.543 --> 12:43.197
[laughs]

12:43.240 --> 12:45.460
<i>- She's actually fallen
three times in the last week.</i>

12:45.503 --> 12:47.288
- Any history of low blood
pressure,

12:47.331 --> 12:49.812
fainting, or seizures?
- Mm-mm.

12:49.856 --> 12:51.292
- You on any new medications?

12:51.335 --> 12:52.815
- No.
I don't take anything.

12:52.859 --> 12:54.904
I think this country
is overmedicated.

12:54.948 --> 12:56.471
- I see you're
an air traffic controller.

12:56.514 --> 12:58.255
- Mm-hmm.
- Pretty stressful work.

12:58.299 --> 13:00.301
- No, I've been doing it
for five years.

13:00.344 --> 13:02.999
I know where all
those little planes are going.

13:03.043 --> 13:05.480
[laughs]
- Impressive.

13:05.523 --> 13:07.787
Brad, can you think
of anything else?

13:07.830 --> 13:10.354
<i>- She hasn't gone to the gym
since the pandemic,</i>

13:10.398 --> 13:13.270
<i>and she stopped her paleo diet
a few weeks ago.</i>

13:13.314 --> 13:15.838
- Yeah, I'm not seeing
anything that concerns me.

13:15.882 --> 13:18.841
But we will get an EKG, labs,
and an x-ray of your arm.

13:18.885 --> 13:21.844
See if we can't find out why
you've been unsteady lately.

13:21.888 --> 13:24.412
- Okey dokey.
- Hang in there.

13:24.455 --> 13:26.980
<i>♪ </i>

13:27.023 --> 13:29.156
- She seem
a little high to you?

13:29.199 --> 13:30.766
- Yeah, maybe.

13:30.810 --> 13:32.986
You know, some people get
a little loopy in the E.D.

13:33.029 --> 13:34.117
- Mm-hmm.

13:34.161 --> 13:35.336
- Add a tox screen
to her bloodwork.

13:35.379 --> 13:37.468
- Yeah.
Blood alcohol?

13:37.512 --> 13:39.166
- Yeah.
Okay.

13:39.209 --> 13:42.169
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:42.212 --> 13:46.216
<i>♪ </i>

13:46.260 --> 13:49.959
Got any change?
- Not yet.

13:51.395 --> 13:54.007
- Dr. Halstead.

13:54.050 --> 13:55.878
Sabeena Virani.

13:55.922 --> 13:58.794
- Ah...
I'm sorry, Dr. Virani.

13:58.838 --> 14:00.883
We were supposed to meet
in the cardiology clinic.

14:00.927 --> 14:03.103
- If this isn't a good time...

14:03.146 --> 14:06.019
- No, it's just...
someone I know.

14:06.062 --> 14:08.499
- I'm sorry.
I'll catch you another time.

14:10.197 --> 14:11.372
- Wait.

14:11.415 --> 14:12.895
You said you work
for Kender Pharma?

14:12.939 --> 14:14.157
- R&D.

14:14.201 --> 14:15.332
We're running
a trial at Med

14:15.376 --> 14:17.030
for an oral heart
failure medication.

14:17.073 --> 14:19.423
Dr. Ramsey is principal
investigator.

14:19.467 --> 14:22.339
He thought it'd be good
to have an E.D. doc as co-P.I.

14:22.383 --> 14:23.950
Recommended you.

14:25.081 --> 14:26.126
- Thanks.

14:26.169 --> 14:28.868
Another time,
I might be interested.

14:28.911 --> 14:30.913
Just--I got a lot
going on right now.

14:30.957 --> 14:34.177
- I understand.
I hope everything works out.

14:39.661 --> 14:43.230
- Dina, status on Mr. Booker.

14:43.273 --> 14:44.884
<i>- Sats are stable.</i>

14:44.927 --> 14:46.581
<i>- Keep me posted.</i>

14:46.624 --> 14:47.930
<i>[radio beeps]</i>

14:47.974 --> 14:49.192
<i>- Ethan?</i>

14:49.236 --> 14:50.846
- Coming to you.

14:50.890 --> 14:52.239
<i>♪ </i>

14:52.282 --> 14:55.198
<i>- Mr. MacNeal,
his sats are 85.</i>

14:55.242 --> 14:57.200
<i>I think you better
talk to his wife.</i>

14:57.244 --> 15:02.597
<i>♪ </i>

15:02.640 --> 15:04.381
<i>- Mrs. MacNeal?</i>

15:04.425 --> 15:06.035
Hi, I'm Dr. Choi.

15:06.079 --> 15:07.384
I've been treating
your husband today.

15:07.428 --> 15:09.952
<i>- Please.
How is he?</i>

15:09.996 --> 15:12.476
- I'm sorry to say
he's not doing well.

15:12.520 --> 15:15.653
His oxygen saturation level
is still only 85,

15:15.697 --> 15:17.612
a good ten points
under what it should be.

15:17.655 --> 15:19.527
<i>- Oh, my God.</i>

15:19.570 --> 15:22.443
- We've done everything we can
with the ventilator--

15:22.486 --> 15:25.315
inhaled nitrous oxide,
100% oxygen--

15:25.359 --> 15:27.491
and unfortunately,
nothing's worked.

15:27.535 --> 15:30.364
<i>- So if the ventilator
hasn't helped,</i>

15:30.407 --> 15:32.148
<i>what else can we--</i>

15:32.192 --> 15:34.020
- There is one more thing
we could try.

15:34.063 --> 15:35.630
It's called ECMO--

15:35.673 --> 15:38.502
it's a life support system that
takes the place of the lungs.

15:38.546 --> 15:40.504
<i>- Life support?</i>

15:40.548 --> 15:41.984
<i>That sounds so--</i>

15:42.028 --> 15:43.594
- It is.

15:43.638 --> 15:45.379
It is, ma'am.

15:45.422 --> 15:47.555
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:47.598 --> 15:49.165
I don't wanna minimize
the seriousness

15:49.209 --> 15:52.342
of your husband's condition.

15:52.386 --> 15:55.128
At this point, I believe
ECMO is his only option.

15:55.171 --> 15:57.217
Do we have your permission?

15:59.132 --> 16:00.568
<i>- Yes.</i>

16:00.611 --> 16:02.700
<i>Of course.
Uh, please.</i>

16:02.744 --> 16:05.486
<i>Save my Freddie.</i>

16:05.529 --> 16:07.618
- I'll do my best, ma'am.

16:07.662 --> 16:10.578
<i>♪ </i>

16:10.621 --> 16:12.667
<i>[computer program closes]</i>

16:14.234 --> 16:16.366
<i>[iPad rings]</i>

16:16.410 --> 16:18.020
<i>- Oh, hey.</i>

16:18.064 --> 16:19.369
- Hi, sweetie!

16:19.413 --> 16:21.067
<i>- Hey.
How's the arm?</i>

16:21.110 --> 16:24.113
- The x-ray is negative.
Her arm is not broken.

16:24.157 --> 16:26.028
- Yay!
It's not broken.

16:26.072 --> 16:27.203
[laughter]

16:27.247 --> 16:29.379
- But there is one thing.

16:29.423 --> 16:30.946
So your labs show you have

16:30.990 --> 16:33.383
a blood alcohol level
of 0.14.

16:33.427 --> 16:35.081
- A what?

16:35.124 --> 16:37.387
- It indicates
that you had alcohol today.

16:37.431 --> 16:39.389
- [laughing]
No, I didn't.

16:39.433 --> 16:41.391
<i>- No.
No way.</i>

16:41.435 --> 16:42.566
- [laughs]

16:42.610 --> 16:44.046
- So I'm just wondering maybe

16:44.090 --> 16:46.353
if that's the reason
you've been falling lately.

16:46.396 --> 16:48.355
- No.
No.

16:48.398 --> 16:50.966
I haven't had
any alcohol today.

16:51.010 --> 16:53.055
- What about last night?
- No!

16:53.099 --> 16:55.057
I don't drink.
I don't like the taste.

16:55.101 --> 16:56.493
Yuck.
- I'll tell you what.

16:56.537 --> 16:59.105
Why don't we get some
more fluids in your system

16:59.148 --> 17:01.063
and we'll be back
to check on you in a bit?

17:01.107 --> 17:02.630
Okay?

17:02.673 --> 17:04.240
<i>- Okay.</i>

17:04.284 --> 17:06.460
- [chuckles]

17:08.027 --> 17:09.289
- She's drunk.

17:09.332 --> 17:12.466
- Well, something's going on.

17:12.509 --> 17:14.555
- I think she has
a serious problem.

17:14.598 --> 17:16.383
- Hey, might be
a one-time event,

17:16.426 --> 17:18.080
you know, set off
by some stressor.

17:18.124 --> 17:20.430
- The woman's fallen
three times in the last week.

17:20.474 --> 17:22.258
Wouldn't you call that
a pattern?

17:22.302 --> 17:23.607
- Hey, her husband said
she doesn't drink.

17:23.651 --> 17:25.566
She doesn't drink.

17:25.609 --> 17:27.002
So, let's monitor her BAC,

17:27.046 --> 17:28.351
and when she comes down,
we'll check, okay?

17:28.395 --> 17:29.744
- Wh--

17:29.787 --> 17:31.311
- Hey.

17:31.354 --> 17:33.182
Kellie Lieu--my peds patient
with leukemia?

17:33.226 --> 17:35.532
- Yeah.
Labs and history just came in.

17:35.576 --> 17:37.317
- Oh, perfect.

17:37.360 --> 17:39.145
[inhales sharply]

17:39.188 --> 17:40.494
- Not good, huh?

17:40.537 --> 17:42.539
- No.
[scoffs]

17:42.583 --> 17:44.498
I need a surgical consult.

17:44.541 --> 17:47.022
- All right.
I'll ask Crockett.

17:47.762 --> 17:49.198
- You know what?
Wait.

17:49.242 --> 17:51.461
Don't page Crockett.
Just page whoever's on call.

17:51.505 --> 17:54.160
- Whoa.

17:54.203 --> 17:55.639
Make sure he gets that.

17:55.683 --> 17:57.119
Why not Crockett?

17:57.163 --> 17:58.294
- Oh, it's nothing.

17:58.338 --> 17:59.426
I just--I need a consult.

17:59.469 --> 18:01.471
And so I was gonna page
the call person.

18:01.515 --> 18:03.125
- Why do that?
I'm free.

18:04.518 --> 18:06.520
- Okay.

18:06.563 --> 18:08.783
- Uh, the patient is
Kellie Lieu.

18:08.826 --> 18:11.351
She's 12.
She's been battling leukemia.

18:11.394 --> 18:14.136
She presented today with
chemo-induced heart failure.

18:14.180 --> 18:15.616
- Is that why you
didn't wanna bring me in?

18:15.659 --> 18:17.183
Kid with leukemia.

18:17.226 --> 18:19.446
'Cause I lost my little girl?

18:19.489 --> 18:22.362
- I just thought maybe it
was a little too close to home.

18:22.405 --> 18:24.146
- Thank you.

18:24.190 --> 18:25.756
Tell me about the patient.

18:25.800 --> 18:29.673
- BNPs 2500,
ejection fraction 15%.

18:29.717 --> 18:30.805
- Bad numbers.

18:30.848 --> 18:32.154
- And it just gets worse.

18:32.198 --> 18:34.504
Her latest blood smear
shows an increase

18:34.548 --> 18:36.724
in elevated cells
in her bone marrow.

18:36.767 --> 18:38.682
- So the cancer's coming back?
- Yeah.

18:38.726 --> 18:40.206
- Okay.
Well, send me the chart.

18:40.249 --> 18:41.598
And what you just did,

18:41.642 --> 18:43.731
that's why I don't tell people
about my past.

18:43.774 --> 18:49.084
<i>♪ </i>

18:52.261 --> 18:54.263
- The leukemia's
gonna come back?

18:54.307 --> 18:56.613
- Yes.
It seems like it is.

18:56.657 --> 18:58.528
I'm so sorry, Mr. Lieu.

18:58.572 --> 19:00.704
- So...

19:00.748 --> 19:02.532
we have to start chemo again.

19:02.576 --> 19:04.447
- Eventually, yes.

19:04.491 --> 19:06.188
But right now, Kellie's
heart's too damaged

19:06.232 --> 19:07.755
for more chemo.

19:07.798 --> 19:10.279
Getting her heart in shape
has to be her first priority.

19:10.323 --> 19:12.673
- Yes.
Okay.

19:12.716 --> 19:13.804
How do we do that?

19:13.848 --> 19:15.458
- Well, there are two options.

19:15.502 --> 19:16.546
The first we talked about--

19:16.590 --> 19:17.852
replace Kellie's
current regimen

19:17.895 --> 19:19.375
with one that's less toxic,

19:19.419 --> 19:20.724
but in addition,
we add Milrinone

19:20.768 --> 19:22.378
to ease the strain
on her heart.

19:22.422 --> 19:24.728
- But we don't know how long
that would take to work.

19:24.772 --> 19:26.339
And if the cancer comes back

19:26.382 --> 19:28.384
before her heart
is healthy for chemo,

19:28.428 --> 19:29.907
we'd have no way to fight it.

19:29.951 --> 19:31.387
- [sighs]

19:31.431 --> 19:33.172
You said there's
a second option.

19:33.215 --> 19:34.390
- Surgery.

19:34.434 --> 19:36.131
Implant an LVAD--

19:36.175 --> 19:38.655
an assist device that will take
the pressure off Kellie's heart

19:38.699 --> 19:40.396
so it can recover faster.

19:40.440 --> 19:41.397
<i>♪ </i>

19:41.441 --> 19:42.616
- Surgery.

19:42.659 --> 19:44.139
- That would be
my recommendation.

19:44.183 --> 19:45.793
- But you have to know,
it comes with risks.

19:45.836 --> 19:47.751
Okay, Kellie is
immunocompromised.

19:47.795 --> 19:50.406
That increases the chance
of post-op infection.

19:50.450 --> 19:52.800
And with COVID,
the danger is even greater.

19:52.843 --> 19:55.368
- So you don't advise surgery?

19:55.411 --> 19:58.197
- Well, we've learned
how to mitigate those risks.

19:58.240 --> 20:01.200
- Still, LVADs are rarely used
in pediatric cases

20:01.243 --> 20:03.245
because they are
tailored to fit adults.

20:03.289 --> 20:04.768
- That's because
there aren't many kids

20:04.812 --> 20:06.335
with Kellie's level
of heart disease.

20:06.379 --> 20:08.294
- If you two don't agree,

20:08.337 --> 20:10.383
how can I make this decision?

20:10.426 --> 20:12.298
- Mr. Lieu, I know h--
[sighs]

20:12.341 --> 20:14.517
We know how difficult this is
but I--

20:14.561 --> 20:15.910
- I don't think you do.

20:15.953 --> 20:18.913
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

20:18.956 --> 20:20.306
<i>♪ </i>

20:20.349 --> 20:23.265
I lost my wife two years ago.

20:23.309 --> 20:25.267
She's not here to help me.

20:25.311 --> 20:28.357
The world is upside down.

20:28.401 --> 20:30.925
[scoffs]

20:30.968 --> 20:34.276
Yesterday, a woman
in the parking lot

20:34.320 --> 20:36.626
pointed at us and screamed,

20:36.670 --> 20:39.716
"You brought COVID here.
It's your fault.

20:39.760 --> 20:42.284
Go back where you're from!"

20:42.328 --> 20:43.807
<i>♪ </i>

20:43.851 --> 20:45.287
[breathes heavily]

20:45.331 --> 20:47.463
I have to worry
about my daughter's leukemia,

20:47.507 --> 20:49.552
the pandemic.

20:49.596 --> 20:51.859
And now that we could
get attacked...

20:51.902 --> 20:53.687
<i>♪ </i>

20:53.730 --> 20:55.471
Who do I trust?

20:55.515 --> 20:57.604
- I'm sorry this
is happening to you.

20:57.647 --> 21:00.520
- All I wanna do
is what's best for Kellie.

21:00.563 --> 21:02.478
The safest thing.

21:02.522 --> 21:04.872
<i>♪ </i>

21:04.915 --> 21:07.570
And that doesn't sound
like surgery.

21:12.706 --> 21:14.795
We'll try the medication?
- All right.

21:14.838 --> 21:17.537
I'll call your oncologist,
and we'll get started.

21:17.580 --> 21:20.844
Thank you.

21:20.888 --> 21:23.673
<i>♪ </i>

21:23.717 --> 21:24.848
- Hey.
- Yeah?

21:24.892 --> 21:26.328
- What's going on with you?

21:26.372 --> 21:27.677
When did you get
so hyper-conservative?

21:27.721 --> 21:30.027
- I thought he should
have all the facts.

21:30.071 --> 21:31.377
- Let me tell you something.

21:31.420 --> 21:32.856
You talked that man
out of an operation

21:32.900 --> 21:36.295
his little girl needs.

21:36.338 --> 21:43.302
<i>♪ </i>

21:43.345 --> 21:45.434
- Thank you.

21:45.478 --> 21:46.870
- What are you doing?

21:46.914 --> 21:49.699
- Dr. Lanik cancelled
Mr. MacNeal's ECMO.

21:51.919 --> 21:54.487
Why did you cancel it?

21:54.530 --> 21:56.532
- Look--he shouldn't have
ordered it in the first place.

21:56.576 --> 21:58.534
- Excuse me.
He's my patient.

21:58.578 --> 21:59.883
- And I'm chief of the E.D.

21:59.927 --> 22:01.842
I have to allocate resources.

22:01.885 --> 22:04.714
We only have four ECMOs
for the entire ward--four.

22:04.758 --> 22:06.281
Three are already in use.

22:06.325 --> 22:07.630
- Which leaves one
for Mr. MacNeal.

22:07.674 --> 22:09.850
- April, I can't tie up
my last circuit on him.

22:09.893 --> 22:11.634
Especially when we know
Mr. Booker,

22:11.678 --> 22:13.332
who still has a chance,
is gonna need it.

22:13.375 --> 22:14.637
- You don't know
he's gonna need it for sure.

22:14.681 --> 22:15.943
And ECMO's the only thing

22:15.986 --> 22:17.379
that could possibly save
Mr. MacNeal's life.

22:17.423 --> 22:19.338
- The man is gonna go
into multi-organ failure.

22:19.381 --> 22:20.513
Over the last six months,

22:20.556 --> 22:22.428
how many times
have we seen this?

22:22.471 --> 22:24.604
ECMO is not gonna
change the outcome.

22:24.647 --> 22:26.301
- You can't say that for sure.

22:26.345 --> 22:27.737
You're just gonna give up?

22:27.781 --> 22:30.740
- We've done
everything we could.

22:30.784 --> 22:32.394
Look, you wanna make me
the bad guy?

22:32.438 --> 22:33.874
Get in line.

22:33.917 --> 22:36.877
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

22:36.920 --> 22:43.927
<i>♪ </i>

22:45.973 --> 22:47.496
- Hey, Crockett.
- Yeah?

22:47.540 --> 22:48.932
Oh, yeah.
She's doing fine.

22:48.976 --> 22:50.586
Aced her spontaneous
breathing trial.

22:50.630 --> 22:51.979
I just extubated her.

22:52.022 --> 22:54.851
You can head in.
- All right.

22:57.550 --> 23:00.640
[sighs]

23:00.683 --> 23:02.468
Hey.

23:02.511 --> 23:04.121
- I'm so sorry.

23:04.165 --> 23:06.428
- It's all right, Hannah.

23:06.472 --> 23:09.431
It's all right.
- No.

23:09.475 --> 23:11.955
No, you trusted me,
and I let you down.

23:11.999 --> 23:14.828
- Hey, the most important
thing is you're okay.

23:14.871 --> 23:17.047
And you will come back
from this.

23:21.922 --> 23:24.968
- When they were taking me
out of the ambulance,

23:25.012 --> 23:28.450
as messed up as I was,
I could still hear you.

23:28.494 --> 23:32.062
<i>♪ </i>

23:32.106 --> 23:33.890
You said "I love you."

23:33.934 --> 23:35.152
[breathing shakily]

23:35.196 --> 23:36.893
- I do.

23:36.937 --> 23:39.461
- [laughs]

23:39.505 --> 23:41.855
<i>♪ </i>

23:41.898 --> 23:44.858
I swear I will
make this up to you.

23:44.901 --> 23:48.078
When I get out of here,
I will go straight into rehab.

23:49.645 --> 23:52.648
[whispers]
I wanna be so good.

23:52.692 --> 23:54.433
- Dr. Halstead.

23:54.476 --> 23:56.826
They need you.

23:58.045 --> 23:59.394
- You rest.

23:59.438 --> 24:02.049
<i>♪ </i>

24:02.092 --> 24:03.616
[alarm blaring]
- I don't want it.

24:03.659 --> 24:05.095
- Okay.
- [grunts]

24:05.139 --> 24:06.488
- Sweetie,
these are electrolytes.

24:06.532 --> 24:07.663
- No.
- You need them.

24:07.707 --> 24:09.578
- No, let me alone.
I wanna go home.

24:09.622 --> 24:11.014
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Hold on, hold on.

24:11.058 --> 24:12.494
Anita, I'm sorry.
Get security in here.

24:12.538 --> 24:13.669
Anita, I'm sorry.

24:13.713 --> 24:14.888
I can't let you leave
in this condition.

24:14.931 --> 24:16.672
- What condition?
There's no condition!

24:16.716 --> 24:17.978
- You're intoxicated.
- No, you're--

24:18.021 --> 24:19.022
- Stay down!
- No, I'm not!

24:19.066 --> 24:20.676
- Okay.
- Earl.

24:20.720 --> 24:21.851
- Let go! Let go of me!
- Hold on to her.

24:21.895 --> 24:22.983
- 50 of Benadryl.
- Got it.

24:23.026 --> 24:24.506
Earl, come up here please.
- No!

24:24.550 --> 24:25.681
- Thank you.
- No!

24:25.725 --> 24:27.553
You can't.
- Okay, hold on, sweetie.

24:27.596 --> 24:28.989
- I wanna go home.
I wanna go--

24:29.032 --> 24:30.730
- Okay.
Sorry.

24:30.773 --> 24:32.862
- [breathing calms]

24:32.906 --> 24:34.734
[alarm stops]

24:34.777 --> 24:37.998
<i>♪ </i>

24:38.041 --> 24:40.696
- You were right.

24:40.740 --> 24:41.958
When am I gonna learn?

24:42.002 --> 24:45.135
<i>♪ </i>

24:45.179 --> 24:46.833
<i>- Dr. Halstead.</i>

24:46.876 --> 24:49.575
- Ms. Goodwin, I have a patient
--an air traffic controller--

24:49.618 --> 24:51.577
who has a drinking problem.

24:51.620 --> 24:53.535
Both she and her husband
refuse to admit it,

24:53.579 --> 24:55.668
so I am going
to inform the FAA.

24:55.711 --> 24:57.060
I wanted to make you aware.

24:57.104 --> 24:58.584
<i>- And you're certain
about this?</i>

24:58.627 --> 24:59.889
- Yes.

24:59.933 --> 25:01.587
Uh, I didn't wanna
believe it at first.

25:01.630 --> 25:03.153
She's very convincing.

25:03.197 --> 25:04.894
But it has been going on
for some time.

25:04.938 --> 25:07.723
And, clearly, both she
and her husband are in denial.

25:07.767 --> 25:09.203
<i>- I see.</i>

25:09.246 --> 25:11.248
<i>Well, she's your patient.</i>

25:11.292 --> 25:13.555
<i>It's your call.</i>

25:13.599 --> 25:16.689
<i>I heard about Dr. Asher.
I'm sorry.</i>

25:16.732 --> 25:18.168
<i>How's she doing?</i>

25:18.212 --> 25:19.735
- Yeah, better.

25:19.779 --> 25:21.476
Thanks for asking.

25:21.520 --> 25:23.565
<i>- Well, you know,
I have no choice</i>

25:23.609 --> 25:26.002
<i>but to report Dr. Asher.</i>

25:26.046 --> 25:27.526
<i>♪ </i>

25:27.569 --> 25:28.701
- I know.

25:28.744 --> 25:30.964
<i>- And as to your patient,</i>

25:31.007 --> 25:33.183
<i>I would encourage you
to make sure</i>

25:33.227 --> 25:36.273
<i>there are no
extenuating circumstances</i>

25:36.317 --> 25:38.014
<i>that you're not aware of.</i>

25:38.058 --> 25:40.843
<i>Because once you make
the call to FAA,</i>

25:40.887 --> 25:44.978
<i>this woman's career
is very likely over.</i>

25:45.021 --> 25:47.937
<i>♪ </i>

25:52.463 --> 25:53.334
- [sighs]

25:53.377 --> 25:55.075
Mrs. MacNeal?

25:55.118 --> 25:57.468
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:57.512 --> 26:00.036
Um...

26:01.429 --> 26:02.822
[sighs]

26:02.865 --> 26:05.128
- This is bad, isn't it?

26:05.172 --> 26:07.130
- The doctors have

26:07.174 --> 26:09.829
reconsidered
your husband's treatment.

26:09.872 --> 26:11.831
They don't feel
ECMO will change

26:11.874 --> 26:14.311
the course of his illness.

26:14.355 --> 26:17.097
- Does that mean--
- I'm afraid yes.

26:17.140 --> 26:20.143
You have to prepare yourself.

26:20.187 --> 26:23.146
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:23.190 --> 26:27.673
<i>♪ </i>

26:27.716 --> 26:29.762
- Can I be with him?

26:29.805 --> 26:30.937
Or hold his hand?

26:30.980 --> 26:32.112
- No.

26:32.155 --> 26:34.331
It would put you
at too much risk.

26:34.375 --> 26:36.203
<i>♪ </i>

26:36.246 --> 26:38.684
- We've been married
for 40 years.

26:40.511 --> 26:44.254
And now he's going to die
without me by his side.

26:44.298 --> 26:46.866
- I wish I could change that.

26:46.909 --> 26:48.389
But I can't.

26:48.432 --> 26:51.740
But he won't die alone.

26:51.784 --> 26:53.829
I will be there.

26:53.873 --> 26:55.526
I promise you.

26:55.570 --> 26:56.832
- Oh.

26:56.876 --> 26:59.008
I want you
to give him something.

27:00.575 --> 27:04.187
I just found this.

27:04.231 --> 27:06.712
It was our first date.

27:09.279 --> 27:10.411
- [sniffs]

27:10.454 --> 27:12.239
[sighs]

27:13.370 --> 27:17.113
<i>♪ </i>

27:17.157 --> 27:19.159
I'll make sure he gets this.

27:23.598 --> 27:25.948
- Deep breaths.
Deeper, thanks.

27:25.992 --> 27:27.384
[alarms blaring]

27:27.428 --> 27:28.864
- Help.
Somebody help.

27:28.908 --> 27:30.213
She can't breathe.

27:30.257 --> 27:33.173
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:33.216 --> 27:35.218
- Kellie?
Kellie?

27:35.262 --> 27:36.437
Hey, sweetheart.

27:36.480 --> 27:37.917
Look at me.
All right?

27:37.960 --> 27:39.266
I know you're scared,
all right?

27:39.309 --> 27:41.181
I just need you to take
slow, deep breaths, okay?

27:41.224 --> 27:43.574
Okay?
There you go.

27:43.618 --> 27:45.011
- S Gallop is worse.

27:45.054 --> 27:46.534
Let's get another echo
and chest x-ray.

27:46.577 --> 27:48.275
- What?
What's happening?

27:48.318 --> 27:51.234
<i>♪ </i>

27:51.278 --> 27:53.410
- Kellie's heart failure
is getting worse.

27:53.454 --> 27:54.890
If we don't act now,

27:54.934 --> 27:56.326
she may not be around
to fight the leukemia.

27:56.370 --> 27:57.893
- Oh, God.

27:57.937 --> 27:59.590
It's that bad?

27:59.634 --> 28:01.070
You wanna operate?

28:01.114 --> 28:02.898
Put in that LVAD?
- That's right.

28:02.942 --> 28:05.074
- Dr. Manning, you were
against it before.

28:05.118 --> 28:06.815
- I have to agree
with Dr. Marcel now.

28:06.859 --> 28:08.295
It's what's best for Kellie.

28:08.338 --> 28:10.514
- All right.
Do the surgery.

28:10.558 --> 28:12.168
- All right, let's get
this girl upstairs.

28:12.212 --> 28:13.169
All right, Trini.
You page Dr. Latham.

28:13.213 --> 28:14.431
Tell him to meet me in the O.R.

28:14.475 --> 28:18.087
<i>♪ </i>

28:18.131 --> 28:19.306
[knocks on door]

28:19.349 --> 28:20.481
- Yeah?

28:22.831 --> 28:23.963
- You got a minute?

28:24.006 --> 28:26.443
- Yes.
Sure.

28:28.968 --> 28:30.926
Have a seat.

28:32.536 --> 28:35.061
- I wasn't being honest
earlier.

28:35.104 --> 28:36.932
Things haven't been good
with Hannah.

28:36.976 --> 28:39.326
In fact, they've been
kind of a hell.

28:39.369 --> 28:42.851
These last months,
if she was having a hard day

28:42.895 --> 28:44.940
or we had a fight,

28:44.984 --> 28:48.030
I was always afraid
she'd start using again.

28:48.074 --> 28:49.118
[sighs]

28:49.162 --> 28:50.946
I was just constantly
on eggshells,

28:50.990 --> 28:52.426
and, uh, she could tell.

28:52.469 --> 28:55.211
She blamed me
for not trusting her.

28:55.255 --> 28:57.039
And I see now

28:57.083 --> 29:00.086
that I-I blamed her
for being an addict.

29:00.129 --> 29:02.915
- Blame, resentment,

29:02.958 --> 29:04.264
tricky stuff, you know?

29:04.307 --> 29:05.613
Hard to--hard to let go of.

29:05.656 --> 29:07.180
<i>♪ </i>

29:07.223 --> 29:08.572
- You were right--

29:08.616 --> 29:10.487
what you said
about addicts and romance,

29:10.531 --> 29:11.967
that, if the romance
goes south,

29:12.011 --> 29:14.013
they'll likely turn to drugs.

29:14.056 --> 29:18.017
- You think that that's
maybe what happened here?

29:18.060 --> 29:21.150
- Hannah and I got
into a huge fight yesterday.

29:21.194 --> 29:23.979
I stormed out of the condo.

29:24.023 --> 29:28.114
The next thing I know,
she's, uh...OD'd.

29:28.157 --> 29:30.507
- Oh, buddy.
I'm sorry.

29:30.551 --> 29:32.901
- Yeah.
That's not the worst of it.

29:32.945 --> 29:34.685
[sighs]

29:34.729 --> 29:37.166
See...

29:37.210 --> 29:40.430
I think I've been
waiting for it to happen.

29:40.474 --> 29:47.481
<i>♪ </i>

29:51.659 --> 29:53.269
Where are we at?

29:53.313 --> 29:55.358
- She's sobering up.

29:55.402 --> 29:58.144
You wanna talk to her?
- Not yet.

29:58.187 --> 30:00.624
This case got
too personal for me.

30:00.668 --> 30:03.062
I need to do some research
and look into this more.

30:03.105 --> 30:09.677
<i>♪ </i>

30:11.418 --> 30:13.507
- Hey.
- Hey.

30:13.550 --> 30:14.682
- I just heard.

30:14.725 --> 30:16.510
Kellie Lieu's surgery
went well.

30:16.553 --> 30:17.903
Congratulations.

30:17.946 --> 30:19.513
- Yeah, yeah.

30:19.556 --> 30:21.950
- I was being overly cautious.

30:21.994 --> 30:24.518
I should've agreed
with the LVAD way sooner.

30:24.561 --> 30:27.521
- Well, not necessarily.

30:27.564 --> 30:29.610
It was a risky procedure.

30:29.653 --> 30:31.438
Could've easily gone
the other way.

30:31.481 --> 30:33.483
- [exhales sharply]

30:37.096 --> 30:39.054
You know, yesterday, I...

30:39.098 --> 30:40.621
<i>♪ </i>

30:40.664 --> 30:44.016
I moved out of my house.

30:44.059 --> 30:47.236
I said goodbye to my son.
[scoffs]

30:47.280 --> 30:50.065
I have been thinking
about him all day,

30:50.109 --> 30:51.719
wondering if I did
the right thing,

30:51.762 --> 30:55.070
if he'll be okay.

30:55.114 --> 30:58.247
I think those feelings
clouded my judgement today.

30:58.291 --> 31:04.950
<i>♪ </i>

31:04.993 --> 31:08.214
- You weren't wrong about me
and kids with leukemia.

31:09.606 --> 31:12.783
Every time I see one,
I think about my little girl.

31:12.827 --> 31:15.003
<i>♪ </i>

31:15.047 --> 31:17.397
[sighs]

31:17.440 --> 31:20.095
You know, we try to protect
them as much as we can.

31:22.315 --> 31:25.318
Until that last moment
when we, uh, we can't.

31:29.235 --> 31:31.715
[exhales]

31:35.502 --> 31:37.634
[clears throat]

31:37.678 --> 31:40.550
Uh, all I'm saying is
you're doing the right thing.

31:40.594 --> 31:42.639
Yeah.

31:42.683 --> 31:45.294
Owen'll be okay.
I'll see you tomorrow.

31:45.338 --> 31:47.035
- See you tomorrow.

31:47.079 --> 31:49.472
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

31:52.998 --> 31:54.042
- [knocks lightly]

31:54.086 --> 31:56.479
- Now what?

31:56.523 --> 31:59.091
- I did some research
and ordered one last test.

31:59.134 --> 32:01.571
I owe you an apology.

32:01.615 --> 32:04.531
We now know
you have not been drinking.

32:04.574 --> 32:06.054
- Finally.

32:06.098 --> 32:08.056
- I gotta be honest with you.
This is a first for me.

32:08.100 --> 32:11.320
You have a condition
called auto-brewery syndrome.

32:11.364 --> 32:13.322
And because of it,
the yeast in your gut

32:13.366 --> 32:15.977
turns certain carbohydrates
into alcohol.

32:16.021 --> 32:17.979
- You never even have
to take a drink.

32:18.023 --> 32:19.546
- Really?
- Yes.

32:19.589 --> 32:21.635
<i>- Why would this happen
all of a sudden?</i>

32:21.678 --> 32:24.072
- So you said Anita
was on a paleo diet.

32:24.116 --> 32:26.466
Very low carbs
but she stopped.

32:26.509 --> 32:28.685
- Yeah, I was hungry
all the time.

32:28.729 --> 32:30.818
- We're not sure why
some people react this way,

32:30.861 --> 32:33.516
but that's probably
what triggered it.

32:33.560 --> 32:35.649
- If you cut out simple carbs
from your diet,

32:35.692 --> 32:37.781
you should be fine.

32:37.825 --> 32:39.522
- [sighs]

32:39.566 --> 32:41.002
- So Maggie's
gonna discharge ya

32:41.046 --> 32:43.787
so you can get out of here.
- Okay.

32:47.617 --> 32:49.358
- And again...

32:49.402 --> 32:51.665
I'm sorry.

32:57.801 --> 33:00.456
Hey.

33:00.500 --> 33:02.632
- Hey.

33:05.722 --> 33:08.551
Look--um...

33:08.595 --> 33:10.727
You know, I've been thinking.

33:10.771 --> 33:13.165
When I get out of rehab, I...

33:13.208 --> 33:15.732
I wanna go somewhere...

33:15.776 --> 33:18.039
Away from here.
Get a fresh start.

33:18.083 --> 33:19.867
<i>♪ </i>

33:19.910 --> 33:21.477
- You wanna leave Med?

33:21.521 --> 33:22.696
- [laughs]

33:22.739 --> 33:24.176
Here, I'm just
the addict doctor.

33:24.219 --> 33:27.831
I always will be.

33:27.875 --> 33:30.704
I was thinking L.A.

33:30.747 --> 33:32.662
Decent weather for a change.

33:32.706 --> 33:35.665
<i>♪ </i>

33:35.709 --> 33:38.799
I want you to come with me.

33:38.842 --> 33:40.714
- Hannah...

33:40.757 --> 33:42.063
I'm not gonna do that.

33:42.107 --> 33:44.587
- You don't have to decide
right away, so.

33:44.631 --> 33:46.807
- No, I'm not coming with you.

33:46.850 --> 33:48.635
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:48.678 --> 33:50.419
[sighs]

33:50.463 --> 33:53.727
<i>♪ </i>

33:53.770 --> 33:56.773
- I was afraid you'd say that.

33:58.993 --> 34:02.518
See, the thing is, Will...

34:02.562 --> 34:05.565
Without you...

34:07.784 --> 34:10.787
I'm worried that...

34:11.962 --> 34:14.878
I'm worried that
I'll start using again.

34:14.922 --> 34:17.098
<i>♪ </i>

34:17.142 --> 34:19.492
- I love you.

34:19.535 --> 34:22.799
But I can't be
the reason you stay sober.

34:23.887 --> 34:25.889
It's not good for you

34:25.933 --> 34:29.502
and it's not good for me.

34:30.764 --> 34:32.592
- [laughs]

34:32.635 --> 34:34.811
[sniffs]

34:34.855 --> 34:41.862
<i>♪ </i>

34:43.646 --> 34:45.822
Who's gonna cut your hair?
[laughs]

34:45.866 --> 34:48.608
Who knows?

34:48.651 --> 34:50.653
Maybe in a year or so,

34:50.697 --> 34:54.831
you'll wanna come
visit Disneyland.

34:56.006 --> 34:58.792
- Yeah.
Maybe I will.

35:00.837 --> 35:03.840
[knocks on door]
- What?

35:06.147 --> 35:07.714
- Hey, I picked up
a little Thai.

35:07.757 --> 35:10.020
You, uh--you hungry?

35:14.851 --> 35:17.027
- I hadn't been out
of the house in months.

35:17.071 --> 35:18.768
I was going crazy.

35:18.812 --> 35:21.119
I just wanted
to see some friends.

35:21.162 --> 35:22.816
None of them were sick.

35:22.859 --> 35:24.600
- Honey, I get it.
I totally understand.

35:24.644 --> 35:26.167
- Jennifer had no idea
that she had it.

35:26.211 --> 35:27.951
She felt completely fine.

35:27.995 --> 35:29.518
- You know, sweetie.
It's okay to feel bad.

35:29.562 --> 35:31.041
It's okay.
I'm really glad that--

35:31.085 --> 35:34.001
- Dad, of course I feel bad.
I gave you COVID.

35:34.044 --> 35:35.176
<i>[tense music]</i>

35:35.220 --> 35:36.830
That's why you're mad at me.

35:36.873 --> 35:39.528
- I'm not mad at you.
- Yes, you are!

35:39.572 --> 35:40.747
You've been walking
around the house

35:40.790 --> 35:42.749
acting like everything's fine,

35:42.792 --> 35:45.534
using that phony, calm voice

35:45.578 --> 35:47.971
but, clearly, it's not fine.

35:48.015 --> 35:49.277
Why aren't you yelling at me
right now?

35:49.321 --> 35:50.844
- Why would I yell at you?

35:50.887 --> 35:53.760
- Because I screwed up!
I could've killed you.

35:53.803 --> 36:00.767
<i>♪ </i>

36:00.810 --> 36:03.813
[crying]

36:08.340 --> 36:11.256
I'm so sorry.

36:12.779 --> 36:14.868
Can you forgive me?

36:14.911 --> 36:16.217
- Oh, sweetie.
Of course I forgive you.

36:16.261 --> 36:19.089
Of course I do.

36:19.133 --> 36:21.048
And you know what?

36:21.091 --> 36:23.006
I mean, I think you're right.

36:23.050 --> 36:25.618
I think I have been angry.

36:25.661 --> 36:27.924
And you know what?
Maybe I...

36:27.968 --> 36:29.230
Maybe I should have told you,

36:29.274 --> 36:31.058
but--but I know you
didn't do it on purpose.

36:31.101 --> 36:34.235
I didn't wanna make you
feel any worse.

36:34.279 --> 36:36.933
Here's the thing
about your dad.

36:36.977 --> 36:40.981
I can be pretty good

36:41.024 --> 36:44.637
with other people's emotions,
but...

36:44.680 --> 36:48.380
sometimes not so much
when dealing with my own.

36:48.423 --> 36:51.252
<i>♪ </i>

36:51.296 --> 36:53.254
So I need you around

36:53.298 --> 36:54.734
to keep me honest.

36:54.777 --> 36:57.650
<i>[emotional music]</i>

36:57.693 --> 37:01.262
<i>♪ </i>

37:01.306 --> 37:04.309
- Pad thai's probably
getting cold by now.

37:04.352 --> 37:07.399
- [exhales]

37:07.442 --> 37:09.270
- So you know I'm not
coming home tonight, right?

37:09.314 --> 37:11.925
<i>- Yeah, I know.
You're helping people.</i>

37:11.968 --> 37:14.928
- But I miss you
and I love you very much.

37:14.971 --> 37:16.190
<i>- I love you too.</i>

37:16.234 --> 37:18.323
<i>Nana and I are making cookies.</i>

37:18.366 --> 37:20.934
- Oh, yeah?
What kind of cookies?

37:20.977 --> 37:22.762
<i>- Chocolate chip.</i>

37:22.805 --> 37:24.285
- Mmm.
[chuckles]

37:24.329 --> 37:26.156
So you're having fun with Nana?

37:26.200 --> 37:28.028
<i>- Yeah.
- Good.</i>

37:28.071 --> 37:29.856
I'm glad to hear that.

37:29.899 --> 37:31.205
<i>- I'm gonna go now.</i>

37:31.249 --> 37:33.120
- Oh, okay.

37:33.163 --> 37:34.774
<i>- Bye, Mom.</i>

37:34.817 --> 37:36.863
- Bye, sweetheart.
Mwah.

37:36.906 --> 37:42.172
<i>♪ </i>

37:42.216 --> 37:44.131
<i>[machinery beeping]</i>

37:44.174 --> 37:46.829
- [regulated breathing]

37:52.357 --> 37:55.273
- BP 55/38.
Sats at 60.

37:55.316 --> 37:57.797
Maxed on pressors.

37:57.840 --> 37:59.146
<i>- He's in multi-organ failure.</i>

37:59.189 --> 38:01.714
We've exhausted our options,
April.

38:01.757 --> 38:03.411
<i>- Turn up his morphine?</i>

38:03.455 --> 38:07.067
<i>- Yeah.
And contact his wife.</i>

38:07.110 --> 38:14.117
<i>♪ </i>

38:17.120 --> 38:18.948
<i>[iPad ringing]</i>

38:18.992 --> 38:21.037
<i>- April?</i>

38:21.081 --> 38:22.952
- Hi, um...

38:22.996 --> 38:25.868
I'm afraid it's his time.

38:28.218 --> 38:31.134
<i>- Let me see him.</i>

38:36.879 --> 38:39.186
<i>Fred?</i>

38:39.229 --> 38:41.188
<i>Freddie?</i>

38:41.231 --> 38:46.802
<i>♪ </i>

38:46.846 --> 38:49.065
<i>I love you, honey.</i>

38:51.938 --> 38:56.116
<i>And I'll miss you every day
for the rest of my life.</i>

38:56.159 --> 38:59.249
<i>But then...I'll see you again.</i>

39:01.077 --> 39:04.037
<i>And we'll be together.</i>

39:04.080 --> 39:07.780
<i>Forever.</i>

39:07.823 --> 39:10.173
[sustained high-pitched tone]

39:10.217 --> 39:13.002
<i>[sobs]</i>

39:15.440 --> 39:17.790
- I'm so sorry.

39:17.833 --> 39:20.053
<i>- [sobbing]
No.</i>

39:25.450 --> 39:32.413
<i>♪ </i>

39:36.939 --> 39:38.419
- [sighs]

39:38.463 --> 39:40.900
Another week.

39:40.943 --> 39:43.555
We remember those gone.

39:43.598 --> 39:45.861
Let's share their names.

39:45.905 --> 39:48.864
<i>[emotional music]</i>

39:48.908 --> 39:55.915
<i>♪ </i>

39:56.568 --> 40:00.093
<i>-</i>Helen-Mae Samuels, 85.

40:00.136 --> 40:03.009
Her kids say
she was a great cook.

40:07.361 --> 40:09.929
- Malcolm Grazer, 44.

40:09.972 --> 40:12.453
Coached his son's
little league team.

40:12.497 --> 40:15.500
- Maria Lopez, 58.

40:15.543 --> 40:18.111
Dedicated, life-long
school teacher.

40:20.156 --> 40:22.332
- Frederick MacNeal.

40:24.160 --> 40:27.468
62, avid stamp collector,

40:27.512 --> 40:29.209
scout master,

40:29.252 --> 40:32.299
and beloved husband
of Beverly

40:32.342 --> 40:35.041
for 40 years.

40:35.084 --> 40:42.091
<i>♪ </i>

41:11.077 --> 41:13.993
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:14.036 --> 41:21.043
<i>♪ </i>

41:40.280 --> 41:43.283
[wolf howls]
